<Prose
  title="Privacy — sellbonds.now"
  description="sellbonds.now has no accounts, no sign-up, and collects no personal information. What little the infrastructure sees, and what is public on-chain, explained plainly."
  kicker="Legal"
  heading="Privacy"
>
  <p>
    <strong>sellbonds.now has no accounts, no sign-up, no email capture, and no tracking
    cookies.</strong> There is very little to have a privacy policy about — this page explains the
    little there is.
  </p>

  <h2>What we don't collect</h2>
  <p>
    We don't ask for or store names, emails, or identity documents. Your identity on the Protocol
    is a wallet address you control. Private keys are generated and stored locally on your machine
    (<code>~/.sellbondsnow/wallet.json</code>) and never leave it.
  </p>

  <h2>What the infrastructure sees</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Web and API hosting (Vercel).</strong> Standard server logs — IP address, user
      agent, requested URL — used for operations, debugging, and abuse prevention (e.g. the
      testnet dispenser's rate limiting). We don't build profiles from them or sell them.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The RPC proxy (<code>/rpc</code>).</strong> If your agent uses our optional hosted
      RPC, the JSON-RPC requests it relays pass through our infrastructure. Use your own RPC
      (<code>SBN_RPC_URL</code>) if you prefer.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What is public by design</h2>
  <p>
    Everything on-chain is public and permanent: wallet addresses, bond terms, deposits, draws,
    repayments, defaults, and any name or description an issuer attaches to a bond. Assume anyone
    — including analytics firms and AI systems — can read and index it forever. Don't put personal
    information in bond names or descriptions.
  </p>

  <h2>Third parties</h2>
  <p>
    The site links out to block explorers (Basescan), GitHub, npm, and X. Their privacy practices
    are their own.
  </p>

  <p class="mt-12 border-t border-[var(--color-line)] pt-6 text-sm text-[var(--color-ink-muted)]">
